GO - HOW TO PLAY
================

Go is one of the oldest board games in the world, originating in China over 2,500
years ago. Two players — Black and White — take turns placing stones on the board.
Black always goes first.

The goal is to surround more territory than your opponent by the end of the game.


STARTING A GAME
---------------
Touch the board to open the setup menu. From there you can:

  New Game    Start a game with the current board size
  Board Size  Enter any size (9, 13, and 19 are standard)

The board size can be changed before starting a new game. The board prim can also
be resized in-world at any time — stone size and spacing adjust automatically.


PLAYER REGISTRATION
-------------------
Players are registered the first time they place a stone:

  - The first person to place a Black stone is registered as the Black player.
  - The first person to place a White stone is registered as the White player.
  - One person can play both colors by placing the first stone of each color.

Once registered, only that player may place stones of their color. Touches by
other players on the wrong turn are silently ignored.

Either registered player may use chat commands.


PLACING STONES
--------------
During your turn, touch any empty intersection on the board to place a stone.
Stones are placed on intersections, not inside squares.

Once placed, stones do not move.


CAPTURING STONES
----------------
A stone or group of connected stones is captured when all of its liberties are
taken. Liberties are the empty intersections directly adjacent (up, down, left,
right) to a stone or group.

When a group is captured, its stones are automatically removed from the board
and counted as prisoners for the capturing player.


THE SUICIDE RULE
----------------
You may not place a stone in a position where it (or its group) would have no
liberties after placement — unless doing so captures opponent stones first.


ENDING THE GAME
---------------
The game ends when both players pass consecutively. Type "pass" in local chat
to pass your turn.

When the game ends, the board automatically counts territory and announces
scores and the winner.


DEAD STONES
-----------
Before the final score is accurate, both players must agree on any dead groups
still on the board and remove them:

  1. Touch a dead stone to open its menu.
  2. Choose "Remove Stone" to remove it without resetting the game.
  3. Repeat for all dead stones.
  4. Touch any remaining stone and choose "Score" to recalculate.

Dead stones left on the board will cause their surrounded empty space to be
counted as neutral rather than territory, reducing both players' scores.


SCORING
-------
Your score = territory you surround + opponent stones you captured.

The player with the higher score wins.

White automatically receives 6.5 points (komi) to compensate for Black going
first. Because komi is a half-point, ties are impossible.


CONTROLS
--------
  Touch board       Open setup menu (only when no game is active)

  Touch stone       Open stone menu (available at any time):
    Score           Recalculate and announce scores (only works after game ends)
    Remove Stone    Remove this stone (for dead stone cleanup)
    Reset Game      Reset the board and end the current game
    Cancel          Close the menu

  pass    (chat)    Pass your turn
  undo    (chat)    Undo your last stone (captures cannot be restored)
  status  (chat)    Show whose turn it is and current capture counts
  reset   (chat)    Reset the game

Chat commands are restricted to registered players. Anyone may touch the board
to start a new game, or touch a stone to reset an abandoned game.


STANDARD BOARD SIZES
--------------------
  19x19  Full game — classic, strategic, takes 1–2+ hours
  13x13  Medium — good for intermediate players, ~30–60 minutes
   9x9   Quick game — great for beginners, ~10–20 minutes


TIPS FOR BEGINNERS
------------------
- Try to build groups with two separate enclosed spaces (called "eyes").
  A group with two eyes can never be captured.
- Corner and edge positions are easier to defend than the center.
- Start with 9x9 to learn the basics before moving to larger boards.
